04794nam a22007695i 9780824874568DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20052005hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029836722  a(OCoLC)1032683345  a(OCoLC)1037978786  a(OCoLC)1042022959  a(OCoLC)1046617424  a(OCoLC)1047027169  a(OCoLC)1049623409  a(OCoLC)1054881097  a97808248745687 a10.1515/97808248745682doi  a(DE-B1597)484180  a(OCoLC)1024024071  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0260002bisacsh0483pa320qDE-1011 aLarmour, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForeign Flowers :bInstitutional Transfer and Good Governance in the Pacific Islands /cPeter Larmour. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Institutional Transfer in Pacific Studies -- t2. Cargo, Culture, and Context -- t3. Institutional and Policy Transfer -- t4. Customary Land Registration -- t5. Constitutions and Representative Democracy -- t6. Public Sector Reform and Anticorruption -- t7. Determinants of Transfer -- t8. Explaining Transfer -- t9 Evaluating Transfer -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWide ranging and cross-disciplinary in its approach, Foreign Flowers focuses on the process of policy transfer in the Pacific and the use of power to achieve it. Many governing institutions in the region have been borrowed, transplanted, or imposed by colonial rule or military intervention from outside. The book attempts to answer several key questions: Where do the governing institutions originate and why are so many of them based on Western models? Why have some transfers succeeded while others have not? What are the effects of transfers? What has been the fate of a particular institution, "the state?" How does "culture" affect the transfer of (and resistance to) institutions? Early chapters identify institutional transfer as a persistent theme in the study of the Pacific, reflected in ideas like cargo cults, homegrown constitutions, invented traditions, and weak states. The author analyzes about forty cases of institutional transfer, beginning with Tonga's borrowing of foreign institutions in the nineteenth century and ending with current attempts to induce island states to regulate their offshore financial centers. He goes on to distinguish factors that determine whether transfer took place, including timing, social conditions, and sympathy with local values. He looks at the kinds of power and coercion being deployed in transfer and at how transfers have been evaluated by their sponsors: domestic reformers, aid donors, international financial institutions, and their consultants and academic advisers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082487456840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824874568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824874568.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12S